Problem:- Subarray Sum Equals K

Given an array of integers nums and an integer k, return the total number of subarrays whose sum equals to k.
A subarray is a contiguous non-empty sequence of elements within an array.

Example 1:
Input: nums = [1,1,1], k = 2
Output: 2

Solutions:-

Subarray Sum Equals K counts contiguous subarrays summing to k using prefix sums + HashMap. O(n) time breakthrough.
​
#Java Implementation (Prefix Sum + HashMap)

class Solution {
    public int subarraySum(int[] nums, int k) {
        Map<Integer, Integer> prefixCount = new HashMap<>();
        prefixCount.put(0, 1);  // Empty prefix
        
        int prefixSum = 0;
        int count = 0;
        
        for (int num : nums) {
            prefixSum += num;
            
            // If prefixSum - k exists, that's our subarray count
            if (prefixCount.containsKey(prefixSum - k)) {
                count += prefixCount.get(prefixSum - k);
            }
            
            // Add current prefix
            prefixCount.put(prefixSum, prefixCount.getOrDefault(prefixSum, 0) + 1);
        }
        
        return count;
    }
}

Prefix insight: sum[i:j] = prefix[j] - prefix[i-1]. HashMap tracks previous prefixes.
​
#Step-by-Step Logic
HashMap: prefix → frequency
prefixCount = 1: Subarrays starting from index 0
For each num:
text
prefixSum += num
if (prefixSum - k exists): count += freq
prefixCount[prefixSum]++
Example trace: [1,1,1], k=2
text
i=0: prefix=1, 1-2=-1? No, map={0:1,1:1}
i=1: prefix=2, 2-2=0 ✓ +1, map={0:1,1:1,2:1} ✓ count=1
i=2: prefix=3, 3-2=1 ✓ +1, map={0:1,1:1,2:1,3:1} ✓ count=2

#Thought Process
Brute O(n²): All subarrays → TLE.
Prefix revelation: sum[i:j] = prefix[j] - prefix[i-1] = k
text
Need prefix[j] - k = prefix[i-1]
HashMap stores all previous prefix[i-1] frequencies.
Why 0:1? Subarrays from start: [1,1] sum=2.

#Edge Cases
k=0: Count subarrays sum 0 (empty prefix handles).
All zeroes: [0,0,0] k=0 → 6 subarrays.
Single element: [2] k=2 → 1.
Negatives: Prefix handles perfectly.
No matches: → 0.
